               <msContents class="#MVM">
                  <summary><p>Dialogues on the Old Testament, that is on Genesis, Exodus, Leviticus, Numbers, and Deuteronomy.</p>
<p>This is the first of the three volumes of a multi-volume manuscript of dialogues (<foreign xml:lang="ta">callāpaṅkaḷ</foreign>) on the Old Testament, that is,  
  <list rend="numbered">
    <item><ref target="https://tst-project.github.io/mss/Indien_0450.xml">BnF Indien 450</ref></item>
    <item><ref target="https://tst-project.github.io/mss/Indien_0451.xml">BnF Indien 451</ref></item>                                                                                                 
    <item><ref target="https://tst-project.github.io/mss/Indien_0452.xml">BnF Indien 452</ref></item>
  </list>
</p>
<p>According to Richard (1989, pp. 161-163), with convincing arguments, this multi-volume manuscript could be the oldest known translation of the Bible into Tamil, made between 1666 and 1677 by the capuchin fathers Ephrem de Nevers (1607/10-1695) and Zénon de Baugé (1603?-1687). More precisely, this is an adaptation, as this is a dialogue between a master and a disciple on the various books of the Bible.</p>
<p>Description based on the examination of the original manuscript (April 2021).</p>
<p>Dimensions assessed at the time of examination.</p>
<p>The images are in the reversed order on Gallica microfilm.</p></summary>
                  
