               <history>
                  
                  
                  
               <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1729" notBefore="1666">1729 at the latest, as described in the list of books sent this year by the Jesuits of Pondicherry.
Dated to 1743-09-13 by Vinson in Vinson et al. (1866-) on the basis of a colophon (28 Purattāci 4844).
Dated to 1743 by Cabaton (1912), on unstated grounds.
There are several internal dates in the manuscript, but it is not clear if these are dates of copy or dates copied from the master copy, if any.
It is not clear if the date 1866 in the final colophon (U2a, <locus facs="2">f324r4</locus>), presumably in the Christian era, is the date of the manuscript copy, a date copied from an antigraph, if any, or the date of the work.</origDate>
                     
                  <origPlace>Pondicherry (?)</origPlace></origin><provenance><p>Acquired or copied in Pondicherry by the Jesuits of Pondicherry.</p></provenance><acquisition><p>According to Vinson in Vinson et al. (1866-), followed by Cabaton (1912), this manuscript is "ancien fonds n° I", which he dates to 1743 though. 

This manuscript indeed appears to be the first of three volumes referred to as a single-volume <ref target="https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/btv1b105278700/f17">Bible</ref> and <ref target="https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/btv1b105278700/f31">Bible en Malabar ou Tamoul</ref> sent by the Jesuits of the Mission du Carnate in 1729 for the library of the king of France and mentioned in ancien lists (BnF NAF 5442, f5r and f9r).
These lists state that this Bible, as well as the next two items in the list <ref target="https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/btv1b105278700/f17">are printed by the Lutheran missionnaries from Tranquebar</ref> and <ref target="https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/btv1b105278700/f31">are from the Danish Protestants.</ref></p></acquisition></history>
